        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-05-21 15:00:53.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n> Patch Set 7:\n> \n> I think with this change you might still get both master and honolulu pushing \"latest\". \n> \n> One way you can control this better, if any of the merge jobs is currently running on a schedule, you might want to set cron: \"\" to disable the schedule. \n> \n> Otherwise, I think you might be able to modify the docker files or pom.xml files (depending on how the project configures their tagging) to disable the \"latest\" tag for one of the branches. I think this is done in the docker files, right?\n\nreg >>I think with this change you might still get both master and honolulu pushing \"latest\"\nI believe the jobs will be setup for both master and honolulu (based on name tag) however since stream/branch are set explicit to honolulu on gerrit-docker-merge-maintainance, both build jobs will always be done for honolulu branch and hence assuming no latest tag generation should happen.\n\nNot sure if there is way to test it in sandbox otherwise we can merge and monitor the jobs. If it doesnt solve the issue, we can revert the change.",
        "patchset_number": 8
